====================================================================
üìå CARDINALITY IN DBMS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
====================================================================

CARDINALITY defines the **number of relationships**
between entities in a database.

It tells us **HOW MANY instances of one entity**
can be associated with **HOW MANY instances of another entity**.

====================================================================
WHY DO WE USE CARDINALITY?
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî To define relationship constraints  
‚úî To design accurate ER diagrams  
‚úî To avoid data redundancy  
‚úî To maintain data integrity  
‚úî To understand real-world relationships  

====================================================================
TYPES OF CARDINALITY
--------------------------------------------------------------------
1Ô∏è‚É£ One-to-One (1 : 1)  
2Ô∏è‚É£ One-to-Many (1 : M)  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Many-to-One (M : 1)  
4Ô∏è‚É£ Many-to-Many (M : M)  

====================================================================
# 1Ô∏è‚É£ ONE-TO-ONE (1 : 1)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
One record in Entity A is associated with
ONLY one record in Entity B.

Example:
Person ‚Üî Passport  

‚úî One person has one passport  
‚úî One passport belongs to one person  

USE:
‚úî When both entities are tightly connected  

====================================================================
# 2Ô∏è‚É£ ONE-TO-MANY (1 : M)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
One record in Entity A can be associated with
MULTIPLE records in Entity B.

Example:
Department ‚Üí Employee  

‚úî One department has many employees  
‚úî Each employee belongs to one department  

USE:
‚úî Most common relationship in DBMS  

====================================================================
# 3Ô∏è‚É£ MANY-TO-ONE (M : 1)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Multiple records in Entity A are associated with
ONLY one record in Entity B.

Example:
Employee ‚Üí Department  

‚úî Many employees work in one department  

NOTE:
‚úî Reverse of One-to-Many  

====================================================================
# 4Ô∏è‚É£ MANY-TO-MANY (M : M)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Multiple records in Entity A are associated with
MULTIPLE records in Entity B.

Example:
Student ‚Üî Course  

‚úî One student enrolls in many courses  
‚úî One course has many students  

IMPLEMENTATION:
‚úî Requires a **junction (bridge) table**  

Example:
STUDENT_COURSE(student_id, course_id)

====================================================================
CARDINALITY VS DEGREE
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî Cardinality ‚Üí Number of relationships  
‚úî Degree ‚Üí Number of attributes  

====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================

‚úî Cardinality defines relationship count  
‚úî Used in ER diagrams  
‚úî Helps database design  
‚úî Prevents data inconsistency  
‚úî Essential for normalization  

END OF NOTES
